2.	When is a permit required for seed collection	Complete 
Whenever you are collecting from a site with reserve status under the National Parks and Reserves Management Act 2002, game reserves, public reserves under the Crown Lands Act 1976 or state forests and forest reserves.

3.	List the information required when preparing a work plan for seed collection	Complete 
Tools and equipment, location, time of year, species required, permits if required, who is collecting, access. Review: changes to environmental conditions, weather, changes to expected flowering and fruiting season, weather or access. Fire, nesting sites or animal habitats. Changes to landholders

4.	What WHS policies and procedures are undertaken prior to collecting and cleaning seed	Complete 
Complete risk assessment, wear PPE, undertake training, clean and maintained tools and equipment, notify a responsible person where you are going if working alone

5.	What equipment can be used for collecting seed above 2m	Complete 
Pole pruner and ground sheet, a rifle can be used with permission to shoot seeds off high branches, ladder, ropes, binoculars, bow and arrow

6.	When collecting seed, what do you look for to ensure fruit is ripe and plants are healthy	Complete 
Correct ripening stage e.g. brown or grey in colour for woody fruit, free of insects, allied pests and disease and true to type

7.	Describe three (3) methods of seed collection	Complete 
Answers could include:
Taking advantage of fallen limbs; pole pruner, secateurs or loppers for removing smaller branched or seed bunches; using a pole pruner to drop small branches or seed onto tarpaulin, hand picking, cover seed lot with hessian or other bags to catch highly dehiscent seed
1)	
2)	
