8.	What sustainability practices should you follow to protect plants and the environment during seed collection	Complete 
Answers could include
•	Collect no more than 20 % of seed from a single specimen
•	Avoid collecting from areas regenerating from fire damage
•	Minimise environmental damage by respecting surrounding plants, watch your step and be wary of nests and habitat of native animals.
•	Take advantage of fallen branches
•	Clean footwear, tools and equipment

9.	a) What is the purpose of collecting seed from similar location to the revegetation site? 

b) What is this called?	Complete 
a)	Species collected from the same or similar location and/or closely matched planting site will have adapted to the same environmental conditions e.g. Rainfall, temperature and basic soil attributes
b)	Provenance

10.	What pests, diseases or weather conditions may be detrimental to collected and stored seed?	Complete 
Mould, mice, boring insects, ants, cockroaches. Rain can cause mould to grow on stored seeds

11.	Outline the procedures that may be used for cleaning seed and storing seed	Complete 
Once collected, fruit and/or seed is separated from leaves, twigs and any other foreign matter. Depending on the species and fruit type, seed can be extracted by leaving in paper bag in warm location, low temperature oven, threshing and winnowing or fermentation process. Seeds need to be dried. Spread seed out on a plate, table or any flat surface and moving around to reduce moisture retention. 
After separation, transfer seed to a dry, pest proof container and label with botanical name, location, date collected. This depends on workplace requirements. You could also record collectors name, Easting and Northing coordinates and number of plants

12.	Explain how biosecurity threats are minimised when collecting and storing seed	Complete 
Bio security is minimised by ensuring clean tools and equipment. Reduce the spread of weeds or pests and diseases that may be at the collection site

13.	Explain what to do if you are unsure of the species collected	Complete 
Take a voucher sample, photograph, and location details

14.	What are the basic requirements for good seed storage?	Complete 
The basic requirements for good storage are to ensure that seed is:
•	collected from fruit that is fully mature
•	weighed
•	well dried and cleaned
•	stored in airtight containers
•	stored at constant temperature
Ziplock bags, air tight containers, some seeds need refrigeration and some can be stored at room temperature. Fill containers and close lids firmly

15.	What is the minimal information required on labelled seed	Complete 
Genus species, date, collector, location


